    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense, but I'm still struggling to visualize the actual \"why\" behind the air moving faster on top. Is it just because the path is longer, or is there something else happening with the air particles themselves as they interact with the surface? I've heard people mention the Coanda effect too, how does that fit in with Bernoulli?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the Coanda effect! It's a fascinating phenomenon that complements Bernoulli's principle. The Coanda effect describes how a fluid jet tends to stay attached to a convex surface. In the case of an airfoil, the air flowing over the curved top surface tends to follow the contour of the wing, which helps to maintain a smooth flow and increases the velocity of the air particles on top.\n\nNow, back to your question about why the air moves faster on top. It's not just because the path is longer; it's also due to the way the air interacts with the surface. As the air flows over the curved top surface of the airfoil, it has to travel a longer distance in the same amount of time compared to the air flowing beneath the flatter bottom surface. This increased velocity on top leads to a decrease in pressure, as per Bernoulli's principle, which ultimately contributes to lift.\n\nSo, the Coanda effect helps to maintain the smooth flow of air over the airfoil, while Bernoulli's principle explains the pressure difference that creates lift. Together, they work hand in hand to make an airfoil an efficient lifting device. Keep in mind that these principles are just part of the bigger picture, and there are other factors",
      "source": "target",
